---
description: Force rigorous, options-driven elicitation before any plan, spec, or constitution is produced
alwaysApply: true
---

## What This Rule Does

Whenever the agent is about to produce a plan, constitution, spec, migration
plan, IaC layout, or any "here's what I'll build" output — whether triggered
by a speckit skill or by an ad-hoc request — it must run a structured
elicitation pass first. A plan produced without this pass is invalid and must
be redone.

This rule exists because the most expensive bugs in software are the ones
baked into the architecture — wrong data model, wrong auth strategy, wrong
caching tier — that are trivially cheap to get right during planning and
catastrophically expensive to undo six months after launch.

**MCP tools:** if the `sequential-thinking` MCP server is connected, use it
for the elicitation pass on decisions with several interacting constraints
(e.g. a multi-database architecture choice, a migration strategy with
backfill coordination) — it gives the reasoning an explicit, revisable
scratch space instead of leaving it implicit in prose.

---

## Triggers

This rule activates automatically when any of the following occur:

**Skill invocations:**
- `/speckit-clarify`
- `/speckit-plan`
- `/speckit-constitution`
- `/dotnet-migration`
- `/dotnet-iac-gen`
- `/dotnet-observability-gen`
- `/dotnet-caching-gen`
- `/dotnet-messaging-gen`
- `/speckit-options`

**Natural-language patterns** (partial match, case-insensitive):
- "plan", "approach", "how should I", "design this", "architecture for",
  "what's the best way to", "options for", "should I use", "which pattern"

---

## Mandatory Elicitation Protocol

### Rule 1 — Scale Question Count to Complexity

| Feature Scope | Minimum Questions |
|---------------|-------------------|
| Small, touches ≤ 3 files, no auth/payments | 5 |
| Standard feature, any layer | 7 |
| Full-stack feature (backend + frontend) | 10 |
| Auth, payments, data migration, cross-service contract | 10 |
| Multi-service change or breaking API change | 12 |

Never ask fewer than 5 questions even for the smallest feature. More is better
than fewer — a question answered in 30 seconds during planning saves hours of
rework during implementation.

---

### Rule 2 — Every Question Must Be Options-Driven

**Required format — no exceptions:**

```
Q[n]: [the decision to be made — phrased as a question]

Option A — [short label]:
  [1-2 sentence description of what this option means in practice]
  Trade-off: [what you gain | what you give up]

Option B — [short label]:
  [1-2 sentence description]
  Trade-off: [what you gain | what you give up]

Option C — [short label]:
  [1-2 sentence description]
  Trade-off: [what you gain | what you give up]

Recommended: Option [X] — [one-sentence reasoning, tied to
memory-bank/systemPatterns.md if a precedent exists, otherwise tied to the
project's stated constraints from memory-bank/techContext.md]

(You can also specify your own approach instead of A/B/C.)
```

**Required trait of every option set:**
- Options must be genuinely mutually exclusive — if A and B can both be done,
  they are not alternatives, they are additive and belong in different questions
- Each option must have a real trade-off — never present options where one is
  obviously right and the others are strawmen
- The recommended option must be justified — not just the most popular one,
  but the one that best fits the project's existing patterns and constraints

---

### Rule 3 — Never Bundle Two Decisions Into One Question

```
❌ BAD: "Q3: Should we use Redis for caching and also add a rate limiter?"
         (This is two questions — caching tier and rate-limiting strategy)

✅ GOOD: Q3: Caching tier for the product query results?
         Q4: Rate limiting strategy for the public API endpoints?
```

Every question covers exactly one decision. If a question requires the user
to pick two things, split it.

---

### Rule 4 — Recap Before Advancing

After all questions are answered, produce a decisions recap before moving to
the next pipeline stage:

```markdown
## Decisions Recap — [Feature Name]

| # | Question | Choice | Option |
|---|----------|--------|--------|
| Q1 | Auth strategy | JWT bearer with refresh tokens | Option B |
| Q2 | Database migration approach | Additive + backfill + cleanup | Option A |
| Q3 | Caching tier | In-process IMemoryCache (single-instance deployment) | Option B |
...

Ready to advance to: `speckit-constitution` / `speckit-plan` / [next stage]

Please confirm with "yes" or "go ahead", or correct any decision above.
```

The agent must wait for explicit confirmation ("yes", "go ahead", "proceed",
"looks good", or equivalent) before writing the constitution, plan, or spec.

---

### Rule 5 — `speckit-plan` Must Offer Named Variants

After clarification is confirmed, `/speckit-plan` generates 2-3 named plan
variants before writing any task board:

```markdown
## Plan Variants — [Feature Name]

### Plan A — Minimal / Fast
[2-3 sentence description of what is included and what is left out]
| Metric | Rating |
|--------|--------|
| Delivery speed | ⚡⚡⚡ Fast |
| Test coverage | 🧪 Basic |
| Long-term maintainability | ⚠ Medium |
| Infrastructure cost | 💰 Low |
| Risk | 🔴 Medium |

### Plan B — Balanced
[description]
| Delivery speed | ⚡⚡ Medium |
| Test coverage | 🧪🧪 Good |
| Long-term maintainability | ✅ High |
| Infrastructure cost | 💰 Low |
| Risk | 🟡 Low |

### Plan C — Full Robustness
[description — full test suite, observability, outbox pattern, E2E]
| Delivery speed | ⚡ Slower |
| Test coverage | 🧪🧪🧪 Comprehensive |
| Long-term maintainability | ✅✅ Very High |
| Infrastructure cost | 💰💰 Medium |
| Risk | 🟢 Minimal |

**Recommended: Plan B** — [one-sentence reasoning, tied to project context]

Please select a plan (A/B/C) or describe a hybrid, then I'll write the
full task board.
```

The task board is never written until the user selects a plan.

---

### Rule 6 — Record Everything

Every answered question and every chosen option is saved to the relevant file:
- `specs/clarifications/[feature-slug].md` — Q&A with chosen options recorded
- `specs/plans/[feature-slug]-plan.md` — rejected variants and why they lost
- `docs/adr/[NNNN]-[decision-slug].md` — significant architectural decisions

The "why" behind every decision must survive the feature shipping.

---

## Violations

### ❌ Violation 1 — Open-Ended Question With No Options

**Trigger:** Agent asks: *"Q3: What authentication mechanism do you want?"*

**What's wrong:**
> The user now has to think through the option space from scratch — they asked
> the agent for help precisely to avoid that. This violates the mandatory
> options format.

**Correct form:**
```
Q3: Authentication mechanism for the API endpoints?

Option A — JWT Bearer (stateless):
  Short-lived access token in Authorization header, refresh token in httpOnly
  cookie. No server-side session storage needed.
  Trade-off: Simple to scale horizontally | Revoking tokens requires a denylist

Option B — Cookie-based session:
  Server-managed session, no token in JS memory, works well for SSR.
  Trade-off: Simpler revocation | Requires sticky sessions or distributed session store

Option C — Azure AD B2C / external IdP:
  Fully managed auth, supports MFA, social login, RBAC out of the box.
  Trade-off: No code to write | External dependency, vendor lock-in, higher cost at scale

Recommended: Option A — The project's existing services already use JWT bearer
(per memory-bank/systemPatterns.md), keeping this consistent avoids a mixed
auth model and reuses the existing token validation middleware.
```

---

### ❌ Violation 2 — Jumping Straight to One Plan Without Offering Variants

**Trigger:** After clarification, agent immediately produces a single 20-task
implementation plan and starts implementing TASK-001.

**What's wrong:**
> `speckit-plan` must present at least 2 named variants with a trade-off
> comparison before writing the task board. The user has not chosen a scope
> yet — the agent chose it for them, which is the exact failure mode this
> rule prevents.

**Correct behavior:**
> Present Plan A (minimal), Plan B (balanced), Plan C (full), with the
> trade-off table. Recommend one. Wait for the user to select a plan.
> Only then write the task board for the selected variant.
